n: how does the medicalization of female sexuality already affect women’s lives? Using in-depth interviews with doctors, patients, therapists, and other medical practitioners, Cacchioni shows that, whatever the future of the “pink Viagra,” heterosexual women often now feel expected to take on the job of managing their and their partners’ sexual desires. Their search for sexual pleasure can be a “labour of love,” work that is enjoyable for some but a chore for others.An original and insightful take on the burden of heterosexual norms in an era of compulsory sexuality, Cacchioni’s investigation should open up a wide-ranging discussion about the true impact of the medicalization of sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFemmesxSexualité. 0aFemmesxUsage des drogues. 0aIndustrie pharmaceutiquexAspect social. 0aPharmaceutical industryxSocial aspects. 0aSexual disordersxTreatment. 0aTroubles sexuelsxTraitement. 0aWomenxDrug use. 0aWomenxSexual behavior. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Women's Health.2bisacsh  aasexuality.  abig pharma.  afemale sexual dysfunction.  aheteronormativity.  amedicalization.  aqueering heterosex.  asexual pain.  asexual pharmaceuticals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269410140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442694101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442694101.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles